[3
Date: Fri, 11 Aug 2000 15:59:05 GMT-3
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: State of Connecticut Press Release, 10 Aug 2000 [edited

Additional Crows Test Positive for West Nile Virus in Conn.,
No spraying scheduled at this time
------------------------------------------------------
The State of Connecticut today identified 8 crows testing positive for West
Nile virus (WNV) in 6 different Connecticut communities. The crows were
collected from 5 Jul 2000 through 31 Jul 2000 and transported to the
University of Connecticut Pathobiology Laboratory (UConn) for necropsy.
Tissue samples were taken to the Department of Public Health Laboratory
(DPH) where the virus was isolated. The Connecticut Agricultural Experiment
Station (CAES) has reconfirmed the positive WNV isolations.
The crows were collected from the following towns or cities:
* Stamford - 3
* Milford - 1
* Greenwich - 1
* Norwalk - 1
* Westport - 1
* Cheshire - 1
"The risk to humans is still low. Despite intensive mosquito trapping and
testing, we have had only one pool of mosquitoes test positive for West
Nile Virus, and that involved mosquitoes collected in Stamford on July 11,"
said Arthur J. Rocque, Jr., Commissioner of the Connecticut Department of
Environmental Protection (DEP).
--
